“Completion of the project will ensure regular supply of water to the areas and save funds that are usually committed to undertaking water trucking,” said Mr Lekalkuli. 

Senator Dullo said the National Irrigation Authority and Water Resources Management Authority (Warma) will sink boreholes at Quri and Kulamawe areas to ensure local communities, schools and public facilities have a regular supply of water. 

Mr Adan Ali, a Borana Community elder, lamented that cases of water-borne diseases were so common in the area and that access to clean water will address the challenge. 

“We have been trekking for many kilometres to access water and the project is a relief for us,” said Mr Jarso Dima from Korbesa. Residents advised to sell some of their advised and not to wait until the animals are emaciated. Situation attributed to failed rains, Covid-19, locust invasion, conflicts and insecurity in arid and semi-arid areas. Nigeria lures just a tiny fraction of oil and gas investment, even though it is Africa's largest crude producer. Judge says the prosecution has made a case against the accused. Dr Magufuli often criticised foreign aid, arguing that Tanzania had the power to fund its own projects.